HW3: Working with tables

Solutions to the following tasks should be presented in an R-Markdown document with output: github_document. Both the R-Markdown document (.Rmd-file) and the compiled Markdown document (.md file), as well as any figures needed for properly rendering the Markdown file on GitHub, should be uploaded to your Homework repository. Code should be written clearly in a consistent style, see e.g. Googles R Style guide or Hadley Wickhams style guide.

Your submitted code should be self-contained and results reproducible for someone having access to the HW_data-repo. It is not mandatory to use the tidyverse, but code should be easily readable and avoid unnecessary repetition of variable names.

Note that there are new data-sets available in the HW_data repository. Downloading them by opening the associated R-project and issue a pull. If it fails, delete the HW_data folder on your computer and clone the repository again according to the instructions in HW2.

Long and wide at Statistics Sweden

Visit Statistics Swedens database and

  • Choose a table that is on wide format (see textbook), convert it to long format using gather and illustrate something that is easier to do in the latter format.

  • Choose a table that has variables as rows (e.g.separate rows for men and women), turn it into tidy format using spread and illustrate something that is easier to do in the latter format.

SL lines

In the files HW_data/StopArea.csv, HW_data/Line.csv and HW_data/JourneyPattern.csv you will find SLs current stops, lines, and the stops on each line. Data is downloaded from TrafikLab, where you also will find some documentation of the variables. Unfortunately, data does not contain information about the order in which each line passes the stops.

  • Figure out and describe how the tables relate to eachother.

  • Ideally, we would like each unique JourneyPatternPointNumber in the JourneyPattern table to correspond to a StopPointNumber in the StopArea table (you should have explained why in the previous task). Check whether this is true by counting the number of unique JourneyPatternPointNumber that is not present in the StopPointNumber column of StopArea.

  • The mismatch observed in the previous task can, for most cases, be explained by a simple coding error involving the number zero. Figure out and resolve this error. Any remaining mismatches can be ignored for now.

  • Present a table of the number of active unique bus stops (i.e.bus stops that is in the journey pattern of a line) in each zone (ZoneShortName in StopArea).

  • Choose a line, and plot the stops as points (x = LocationEastingCoordinate, y = LocationNorthingCoordinate) with the name of each stop as a label (e.g.using geom_text). Write the code in such a way that it is easily reusable if you want to plot another line.

If you want a map as backgound, you may want to check out the ggmap-package. Unfortunately, downloading Google maps using this package now requires an API key (requires you to register and enable billing at Google developers). A basic map of Stockholm created by stockholm <- get_map("Stockholm") is available in the file HW_data/Stockholm_map.Rdata. Try it by

library(ggmap)
load("../HW_data/Stockholm_map.Rdata")
krftriket <-  data.frame(lon = 18.055, lat = 59.357, name = "Krftriket")
ggmap(stockholm) + geom_point(data = krftriket, aes(x = lon, y = lat)) +
    geom_text(data = krftriket, aes(x = lon, y = lat, label = name), nudge_y = .003, color = "red")
